post_text:
September 11, 2020 Students in Mrs. Ofsanko's class at BTES had a great day! What was it like? Imagine this: You meet your teacher at the classroom door & she hands you a flashlight to find your desk. Your classroom is dark except for the digital crackling fire & night sky on the front board. Once you find your seat, you're greeted by a sweet welcome treat: swedish fish. You are O-fish-ally in for the Swedish year yet after all! You also see an inspirational poem on your seat titled, "The Road Not Taken" by Robert Frost.
Your campsite is all around you. You look up at the front board & it says, "Welcome to Our Campsite" in gold, fancy glittering letters. You wonder, "Am I in a classroom?" or "Is it still summer & I am dreaming that I am camping in the woods?" As the day moves on, you camp out with a great book, "Frindle," play outside, talk & get to know new friends and paint kindness rocks to honor the heroes of Sept. 11th.

August 7 at 9:35 AM ·

New York, NY— August 7th, 2020 — Bayville, NJ artist, 11 year old Isabella work has been selected by Rockefeller Center to be part of its public art installation in New York City. The International design challenge asked artists to design flags that represented their love for New York City.

Isabella’s work can be seen both in the plaza and flying high on one of the flagpoles in the public art installation (normally the flags of the members of the United Nations fly there). Over 1,200 entries were received from around the world and only 180 were selected. Each winning design was made into an 8-foot by 5-foot flag. “My design represents my point of view of how we’ve been living these past few months…through a computer. My original characters represent all different types of people coming together to keep each other strong. I added my twist to the Hamilton poster with my original character because we had Hamilton tickets but the show was canceled because of Covid-19,” said Isabella.
text:
Berkeley Township School District added 3 new photos.
August 7 at 9:35 AM ·

New York, NY— August 7th, 2020 — Bayville, NJ artist, 11 year old Isabella work has been selected by Rockefeller Center to be part of its public art installation in New York City. The International design challenge asked artists to design flags that represented their love for New York City.

Isabella’s work can be seen both in the plaza and flying high on one of the flagpoles in the public art installation (normally the flags of the members of the United Nations fly there). Over 1,200 entries were received from around the world and only 180 were selected. Each winning design was made into an 8-foot by 5-foot flag. “My design represents my point of view of how we’ve been living these past few months…through a computer. My original characters represent all different types of people coming together to keep each other strong. I added my twist to the Hamilton poster with my original character because we had Hamilton tickets but the show was canceled because of Covid-19,” said Isabella.

post_text: June 15, 2020 Meet Mrs. Ofsanko's & Mrs. Jeffers' "Making Connections" chain challenge winner!! In September, the students were tasked with finding as many text-to-text connections as possible & the student with the longest chain by the end of the year would earn a $20 Amazon gift card. All the students did an amazing job finding meaningful & deep commonalities in their reading. This young lady worked extremely hard and her chain stretched from one end of the classroom to the other even though the project was cut short in March. Congratulations!

May 26, 2020 As the month of May comes to a close we would like to share a wonderful 21 page Feelings Journal from GoZen! This journal helps children identify feelings, learn how to understand what they are feeling, and transform feelings. For more information please click on the link below.
https://gostrengthsftp.s3.amazonaws.com/Printables/FeelingsJournal_GoZenPrintables.pdf
shared_text:
GOSTRENGTHSFTP.S3.AMAZONAWS.COM

May 21, 2020 You may have heard that in February, as part of a long standing tradition, CBW's Kindergarten class sold popcorn and raised $576 to benefit the Popcorn Park Zoo in Forked River. The students voted to choose an animal to sponsor and came up with a tie! With the help of their teachers they were also able to donate to the Rescue Fund and purchase gift cards for the shelter. Even though animal control officer, Maria, wasn't able to visit the students to say thank you she still has a special message she sent for the kindergartners. Best of all, because of a Target Field Trip Grant each student will receive a ticket and popcorn coupon to use with their family!

post_text: May 1, 2020 BTES students have always focused on random acts of kindness throughout the school year. One of our many projects we focused on this year was "Pay it Forward Postcards" which shared some kindness within our school and our community. We will be posting one positive postcard a day on our BTSD Facebook page. Our hope is that everyone who sees the postcard 'pays it forward'. Our goal is really simple, make someone smile, make them laugh, or just make their day a little better. Thanks for playing.

April 25, 2020 A huge congrats to the 5th Grade BTES Stock Market Team for finishing not only in 1st place in the region, but 1st place in the entire State of New Jersey for both the Spring and Full Year Games. They beat out over 2,796 teams including all grade levels through 12th grade, amassing a whopping 335,000 dollars during the Full year and Spring games. Also, a congrats to Mr. Steinmetz for finishing as the #1 coordinator/teacher in the State of New Jersey!
